üöô The Ministry of Internal Affairs presented new rules for obtaining a driver's license Ukraine plans to introduce significant changes in driving schools for obtaining a driver's license, the Main Service Center of the Ministry of Internal Affairs announced. The latest technologies will be introduced into the exam process to make them as transparent, accessible and efficient as possible. What are they planning to introduce? Verification and access to the exam class is planned - a person who passes the theoretical exam will enter the exam class, where there will be a camera at the entrance. It will recognize the face of the driver candidate, which will allow the person to be directed to a randomly determined workplace in the Unified State Register of the Ministry of Internal Affairs to pass the theoretical exam. üëâ The theory exam will be held in the examination classroom under the following conditions: - FACE ID identification of the person during the entire examination process; - fixation of the face and screen in case of a negative answer to the exam question; - prevention of remote access to workplaces; - control over the behavior of the person; - video recording of the exam process. üëâ cars in the service centers of the Ministry of Internal Affairs will be equipped with a video recorder with 4 cameras - front, rear, two interior projections, an internal monitor to control the angle and operation of the video recorder, alarm sensors and duplicate pedals. üëâ purchase of vehicles with built-in technical equipment of various categories for the service centers of the Ministry of Internal Affairs. That is, now future drivers do not need to look for trucks, cars with trailers, motorcycles for rent, if they are not in the service center of the Ministry of Internal Affairs. Now all these vehicles will be there, and everyone will be able to pass a practical exam. üìπ In addition, it is planned to bring video web cameras located on workstations in the classroom to the examiner's workplace, which will allow you to control the entire process online.

SBU announces first suspicions for shelling of civilian objects in Ukraine: evidence on Russian general and Russian Navy admiral collected SBU investigators collected high-quality evidence base on two representatives of the Russian high command, who are responsible for shelling of civilian objects in Ukraine. One of them is the Commander of the Long-Range Aviation of the Russian Aerospace Forces, Colonel-General Serhii Kobylash. And the other is the former Commander of the Black Sea Fleet of the Russian Federation Admiral Igor Osipov. Both of them were notified of suspicion under two articles of the Criminal Code of Ukraine: ‚ñ™Ô∏è Part 2 of Art. 437 (planning, preparation, outbreak and conduct of aggressive war); ‚ñ™Ô∏è—á. 3 Art. 110 (encroachment on the territorial integrity and inviolability of Ukraine). The maximum sanction of the articles provides for punishment in the form of life imprisonment. Thus, during the investigation, the SBU investigators found that since the beginning of the full-scale invasion, Serhiy Kobylash has been following the instructions of the highest military and political leadership of Russia to destroy Ukrainian cities. It is on his orders that Russian invaders carry out massive missile attacks on residential buildings, hospitals and critical infrastructure in different regions of Ukraine. The amount of assistance depends on the cost of housing and communal services used by the family and its income level. ‚è≥9:00 Minute of silence üïØ Military pilot Roman Pasulka died on February 24, 2022 in an air battle with Russian occupiers, defending Kyiv region. He was 22 years old. Roman was born in the village of Raukhivka, Odesa region. In childhood, he moved with his family to Chernihiv region. He studied at Nizhyn school ‚Ññ17. Subsequently, he chose the military path. In 2021, he graduated from the Kharkiv National Air Force University named after Ivan Kozhedub, where he received the qualification of a 3rd class pilot. After graduation, he served in the 40th Tactical Aviation Brigade of the Air Force of the Armed Forces of Ukraine, which is located in Vasylkiv, Kyiv region. He flew on MiG-29 fighter aircraft. On the first day of the full-scale war, Roman defended the Ukrainian sky. He held back the attack of the Russian military, covering his colleagues and protecting civilians. "On February 24, when Russian troops shamefully invaded the territory of Ukraine, Roman received a combat mission and without hesitation took to the skies to defend his homeland. Saving thousands of civilian lives - at the cost of his own life. In the memory of colleagues, Roman will forever remain sincere, smiling, full of many plans for life, which, unfortunately, were not destined to come true. His parents brought Roman up to be a real warrior, strong-willed and courageous patriot of his homeland... Roman was a good student, despite his young age - a professionally trained pilot," - the brigade informed. Senior Lieutenant Pasulka was posthumously awarded the Order "For Courage" of the III degree. The officer was buried in Nizhyn, Chernihiv region. Roman is survived by his parents, sister and beloved girlfriend.
